We recommended the Management to;

Mandate the GSO and the Accountant to promptly and meticulously post the acquired PPEs and any movements and information of the PPEs based on the source documents of the transactions to the respective ledger and property cards.

Submit to the Office of the Auditor the PIP;



Comply with the guidelines and procedures on inventory taking as provided in COA Circular 2020-006 and subsequently submit RPCPPE to the office of the Municipal Accountant;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to reconcile RPCPPE with their records and effect necessary adjusting entries when necessary and the copy which shall be furnished to the Office of the Auditor;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify those previously recognized PPE but with cost below the new capitalization threshold of P50,000.00 into semi-expandable properties and submit the copy of the JEV as well as the list of these items to the resident auditor; and

Direct the GSO to prepare and issue the ICS for those items reclassified from PPE to semi-expandable properties.

We recommended the Management to strengthen the control on the management of inventories of the Municipality by:

Direct the Program-in-Charge to document and report the result of distribution of inventories to the Accounting Office for the recording of the derecognition of the distributed items;

Designate a warehouse or a storage area controlled by the GSO so that proper management and control over inventories can be administered;

Prepare appropriate RIS for those inventories already issued and utilized by the end user;

Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of inventories every semester and submit the RPCI to the Accounting Office and Supply and Property Office as well as to the Resident Auditors;

Direct the Accounting Office to record immediately any necessary adjustments or derecognition upon receipt of the report from the Officer-in-Charge; and

Direct the Accounting Office to regularly reconcile the balances of inventory accounts with the RPCI from the Inventory Committee.

We recommended the Management to:

Post a listing of vacancies on three conspicuous places within the municipality and prioritize and consider filling-up the vacant positions by hiring new employees or expedite promotion of deserving employees to enhance its services;

Ensure that employees who are designated to other positions do not hold incompatible duties/function.

We recommended the Management to:  

Strictly observe prudence in the use of government funds for meals and snacks by ensuring that these are utilized only for expenses which are regular and necessary;

Discontinue the provision of meals and snacks during the conduct of regular meetings and activities which are embedded in the regular functions and responsibilities of the concerned officials and employees;

Keep expenses within the budget; and

Stop the practice of charging Representation Expenses to other accounts.

Identify specific disaster-related projects/activities to be charged under the said funds and iclude in the Annual LDRRMF Investment Plan and incorporate in the Local Development Plan, under a separate caption, the list of all projects and activities to be charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years and the savings made from the continuing appropriations of the LDRRMF for capital outlay;

Monitor the efficient and effective implementation of all programmed projects identified to optimize the utilization of fund, and to guarantee that the goals and objectives of reducing disaster risk and enhancing disaster preparedness and response capabilities will be achieved; and henceforth,

Strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2012-002.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

to conduct a risk assessment; 
to identify critical processes and functions; 
to determine scenarios that may disrupt regular operation; 
to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis; 
to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed; and
to submit a plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We also recommended that Management improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

We reiterate our recommendation that Management ensure to:
Exercise prudence and fiscal discipline in the use of government funds for meals and snacks by ensuring that such expenditures are utilized only for expenses which are regular and necessary;
Discontinue the provision of meals and snacks during the conduct of regular meetings and activities which are embedded in the regular functions and responsibilities of the concerned officials and employees;
Keep expenses within the budget; and
Stop the practice of charging Representation Expenses to other accounts.

Based on the foregoing, we recommend that management direct the following courses of actions:

To the Municipal Assessor:

Regularly prepare the Assessment Roll to be submitted to the Municipal Treasurer’s Office in order for the latter to update their Taxpayers’ Index Cards on a timely basis.

To the Municipal Treasurer:

Recompute the RPT and SET Receivable based on the RPT Register/ Taxpayer’s Index Card and determine the accumulated RPT and SET Receivables as of a designated cut-off date;

Submit the result of recalculation to the Municipal Accounting Office for reconciliation purposes;

Moving forward, prepare and submit the Certified List of Delinquent Taxpayers at the end of the year and ensure that the amount of the delinquent taxes was incorporated in the established receivable amount to be submitted to the Municipal Accountant;

To the Municipal Accountant:

Ensure that the delinquent taxes and the report submitted by the MTO are reconciled in order to achieve the accurate figure to be recognize;

Coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer’s Office in setting up the RPT and SET Receivable on the first day of the year; and

Prepare necessary adjustments to reconcile the amount of RPT and SET Receivables based on the result of recalculation made by the Municipal Treasurer’s Office.

